<materialsCitation pageId="103" pageNumber="381">Masset, Graham Island, Queen Charlotte Islands, British Columbia, Canada.</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="103" pageNumber="381" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="103.[747,1341,2232,2652]" pageId="103" pageNumber="381">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Rhoads" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[749,966,2347,2376]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Peromyscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="103" pageNumber="381" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="keeni">Peromyscus keeni</taxonomicName>
is in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1845" box="[1115,1273,2347,2376]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Peromyscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="103" pageNumber="381" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="maniculatus">maniculatus</taxonomicName>
species group. It was considered a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1845" box="[794,994,2426,2455]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Peromyscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="103" pageNumber="381" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="maniculatus">P. maniculatus</taxonomicName>
, but chromosome and DNA evidence supported recognition as a distinct species. This taxonomic revision resulted in 16 subspecies of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1845" box="[1149,1341,2540,2573]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Peromyscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="103" pageNumber="381" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="maniculatus">P. maniculatus</taxonomicName>
being realigned as subspecies of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Rhoads" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[1232,1334,2579,2612]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Peromyscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="103" pageNumber="381" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="keeni">P. keeni</taxonomicName>
. Eighteen subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
